Project Report

Python Princessess

Author

Avanti Parkhe, Ava Serin, Emily Zhang, and Ada Zhong

Published

May 23, 2023

Abstract
This report aims to develop the most accurate predictions of median house value of Boston neighborhoods based on the features of each neighborhood. We developed ridge, lasso, decision tree, bagged decision trees, MARS, bagged MARS, random forest, XGBoost, and ensemble (voting and stacking) models. Our models were optimized for RMSE to penalize large errors and be sensitive to outliers. Ultimately, the best model was XGBoost, which returned a test RMSE of 2.709. Based on this model, we identified key recommendations to stakeholders. First, prospective homeowners should understand that areas with low-income residents and properties with lower average number of bedrooms are correlated with less expensive properties. Next, realtors and Boston housing authorities can better predict the fluctuations of house prices based on the trends in the aforementioned important features. That being said, stakeholders should be aware that our model may grow obsolete with time as the housing market changes in the future..

1 Background / Motivation

What motivated you to work on this problem?

Mention any background about the problem, if it is required to understand your analysis later on.

We were motivated to analyze this problem as we are college students nearing graduation who want to learn about what factors influence house prices, as finding housing after graduation is a complex process. One member of our group is interested in moving to Boston post-grad, so we figured this dataset would be fitting to our particular needs.

2 Problem statement

Describe your problem statement. Articulate your objectives using absolutely no jargon.

We are attempting to predict the median house price of Boston neighborhoods, in thousands of dollars, based on the characteristics of each neighborhood. This is a prediction problem because the response variable, median_val, is continuous and quantitative.

3 Data sources

What data did you use? Provide details about your data. Include links to data if you are using open-access data.

Our dataset is the Boston Housing Dataset. The dataset contains 14 columns, where median_val is the response variable. This corresponds to the median house price per neighborhood. This dataset was published by the University of Torontoâs Data for Evaluating Learning in Valid Experiments website. It contains housing information collected by the U.S Census Service regarding housing in the area of Boston. The dataset came as a .tar.gz file. We then converted this file into a csv file. The documentation and data are linked below.

https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~delve/data/boston/bostonDetail.html

4 Stakeholders

Who cares? If you are successful, what difference will it make to them?

Our primary stakeholders are current and prospective Boston residents, local realtors, and Boston housing authority. Our project will benefit current and prospective Boston residents because they will be able to better predict house prices and budget more efficiently. Local realtors will be able to market house prices more accurately and have better information on what houses to present to certain clients. The Boston housing authority can benefit by having more information on what neighborhoods have more affordable housing.

The data preparation we did was dependent upon the model. The code is in the code file in the respective model sections. For the models that required a train, test split, (i.e.Â all of the models except Ridge, Lasso, Stepwise) we used the train_test_split feature of scikit learn with an 80/20 split of the train and test data. For ridge and lasso, we also did a log transformation on the response variable because there was a slight right skew in the data. More specific information can be found in the respective sections if any.

7 Approach

What kind of a models did you use? What performance metric(s) did you optimize and why?

Is there anything unorthodox / new in your approach?

What problems did you anticipate? What problems did you encounter?

Did your problem already have solution(s) (posted on Kaggle or elsewhere). If yes, then how did you build upon those solutions, what did you do differently? Is your model better as compared to those solutions in terms of prediction accuracy or your chosen metric?

Important: Mention any code repositories (with citations) or other sources that you used, and specifically what changes you made to them for your project.

Our team sought to optimize our predictive modelâs performance by using the root mean squared error (RMSE) as the metric of choice. RMSE is an effective tool for predicting Boston housing prices due to its ability to penalize large errors and its sensitivity to outliers. Both of these traits are critical, as substantial errors can lead to financial losses. Additionally, RMSE uses the same units as the response variable (in this case, thousands of dollars), which facilitates the interpretability of results for stakeholders. It should be noted that despite the existence of solutions on Kaggle for this dataset, we independently developed our models and sourced our dataset from an alternative location.

We started with a naive linear model as a baseline with an RMSE 5.214. Our modeling approach then included the creation and tuning of several models: MARS, bagged MARS, random forest, decision tree, bagged decision tree, ridge and lasso regressions, backward stepwise regression, XGBoost, and an ensemble model containing bagged decision trees, XGBoost, and random forest models, all with the goal of reducing the RMSE.

As we progressed, we encountered several challenges. We anticipated some, such as the long runtime associated with models like gradient boosting, which ultimately led to our decision to use the XGBoost model. However, other challenges were unexpected. We observed that some of the finely tuned models, such as the XGBoost and RandomForest and all tuning iterations for the unbagged decision tree models, exhibited poorer performance than we initially predicted. These experiences underscore the complexity and nuance involved in model selection and tuning.

8.1 MARS, Bagged MARS, Ensemble Model

By Avanti Parkhe

I started by finding the optimal degree of a single MARS model by using this code:

degrees = range(1, 5)

cv = KFold(n_splits=5, random_state=1, shuffle=True)

mse_list = []

for degree in degrees:

    model = Earth(max_terms = 1000, max_degree=degree)

    mse = -cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error').mean()

    mse_list.append(mse)

optimal_degree = degrees[mse_list.index(min(mse_list))]

After getting this optimal degree, I made a MARS model and printed the model summary and RMSE. After this, I chose to bag the MARS model with the average predictions of both 10 and 50 models. I did this using a for loop and taking the predictions of each model within the for loop. I then found the RMSE for these predictions and eventually concluded that the bagged MARS models with 50 models resulted in the lowest RMSE.

Voting ensemble

We did a simple voting ensemble with equal weights that returned an RMSE of 2.796. We then chose to go with stacking ensembles for the RMSE. In order to tune this model, I used the previous models that had been tuned with the best hyperparameters. These were the individual models used, with the hyperparameters obtained from previous tunings done by others.

model_rf = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=1200, max_depth=20, max_features='sqrt', min_samples_split=2,

model_xgb = XGBRegressor(random_state = 1, max_depth = 8, learning_rate = 0.1,
                    n_estimators = 1200,reg_lambda = 1, gamma = 10, subsample = 0.5).fit(X_train, y_train)

Stacking ensemble

We did 3 different models as the metamodel for the Stacking ensemble: Linear Regression, Lasso, and MARS. The Linear Regression metamodel returned a RMSE of 2.772. The Lasso metamodel returned a RMSE of 2.767, and the MARS metamodel returned an RMSE of 2.908. The models that were used in the Stacking ensemble were the same as the ones used above. For each of the metamodels, there was a different input in final_estimator.

Ensemble of ensembled models

Ensembling of all stacking regressor models resulted in an RMSE of 2.732. This model was not tuned; the 3 different metamodels of the Stacking ensemble were used.

10 Limitations of the model with regard to prediction

Are you confident that you found the optimal hyperparameter values for each of your individual models, and that your individual models cannot be better tuned? Or, are there any models that could be better tuned if you had more time / resources, but you are limited by the amount of time you can spend on the course project (equivalent to one assignment)? If yes, then which models could be better tuned and how?

Will it be possible / convenient / expensive for the stakeholders to collect the data relating to the predictors in the model. Using your model, how soon will the stakeholder be able to predict the outcome before the outcome occurs. For example, if the model predicts the number of bikes people will rent in Evanston on a certain day, then how many days before that day will your model be able to make the prediction. This will depend on how soon the data that your model uses becomes available. If you are predicting election results, how many days / weeks / months / years before the election can you predict the results.

When will your model become too obsolete to be useful?

While we hold considerable confidence in having discovered optimal hyperparameter values, the nature of using RandomizedSearchCV for tuningâcoupled with our own informed assumptions on the starting points for the searches and the strategy to fine-tune our modelsâleaves some room for uncertainty. Moreover, due to time constraints and computational expenses, we had to forego consideration of several models including AdaBoost, GradientBoost, CatBoost, and Bagged Random Forest, to name a few. Specifically for our ensemble model, we employed a greedy strategy, tuning each model individually rather than optimizing the ensemble as a cohesive whole.

The task of data collection, albeit straightforward in theory, has its practical challenges. Itâs feasible to gather information from resources like the US Census and local government databases, but the frequency and ease of data collection can vary greatly among different predictors. For instance, the US Census is carried out every ten years, rendering information such as household income and racial proportions in Boston-area towns sporadically updated. Given the volatility of the housing market, relying on these parameters for accurate housing price prediction seems implausible. However, other predictors like proximity to the Charles River and nitric oxide concentration have more frequently updated and readily available data, making them reliable predictors.

The dataset we used hails from 1996, predating the 2008 U.S. housing crisis. Considering the substantial fluctuations in housing prices due to factors like inflation, this model may already be outdated in its specific accuracy of predicting current housing prices. Despite this, it does offer valuable insights into the key features involved in predicting housing prices, which could retain their relevance even today.

11 Conclusions and Recommendations to stakeholder(s)

Based on our model development, XGBoost is the optimal regressor with a test RMSE of 2.709. From this final model, the features stakeholders must pay attention to most if they are concerned with median house prices by neighborhood are low_inc, avg_rooms, and nitric_oxide. That being said, stakeholders should be aware of the fact that our model may grow obsolete with time, as specified in the previous section, though it can still be used for recent data. A new model based on housing in the 21st century would have to be developed to continue predicting median house price by neighborhood accurately, and it is unclear whether this new model would contain the same feature importances.

For prospective Boston homeowners/residents, they should understand that proportion of low income residents and properties with lower average number of bedrooms are correlated with the least expensive properties. As such, when searching for places to live on platforms such as Zillow or Boston Pads, these individuals should filter for homes that contain the maximum number of bedrooms they are interested in. While income information is harder to come by, they can Google the average income of Boston neighborhoods or review Census data.

Realtors and the Boston Housing Authority should understand that the aforementioned most important features are critical in predicting house prices. As such, they should monitor current companies that are developing properties in Boston and see if these organizations are trending more towards family homes, apartments, duplexes, etc. as these are associated with the number of rooms per dwelling. They should also monitor trends in employment, neighborhood demographics, education, etc. as these are all associated with the income of residents. The only domain expertise that may be missing for finding information on nitric oxide concentration; here, they may have to seek out scientific government authorities to find the most up-to-date statistics.

That being said, stakeholders wanting accurate predictions on median house values should take a bigger picture view that does not solely focus on the predictors in this dataset. The state of the economy, local and national politics, distance to educational institutions, etc. are all critical predictors. Ultimately, while we were able to reduce our RMSE significantly from our first, naive linear regression, there are a multitude of factors at play in this problem.
